<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-17</title>

<p>This run covered the 2026-06-16/17 paper pool. Three threads stood out because they attack the same bottleneck from different sides: <b>how to represent heterogeneous embodied experience so that models can act, simulate, and move rather than just summarize video</b>. ACE-Ego-0 turns large-scale egocentric human video into action-level VLA supervision by aligning coordinate frames, embodiments, and time, then reliability-weighting the noisy labels. ActWorld argues that interactive world models fail at object interaction not because they lack capacity, but because their memory is organized by recency rather than by action events. MotionVLA shows that a single motion tokenizer cannot faithfully encode both low-frequency pose semantics and high-frequency physical dynamics, and fixes it with a dual-stream frequency decomposition. Together they suggest the next embodied-AI gains will come from representation engineering and memory design, not only from more data or parameters.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> <i>ACE-Ego-0</i> is the clearest seed for a research run. It directly addresses the robot-data scaling bottleneck, ships strong sim and real-robot numbers, and exposes a concrete design question—how to supervise a policy with noisy pseudo-actions—that the reliability-aware auxiliary loss answers with measurable impact.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 1: Learning from human data for robot action</h1>

<p>Robot teleoperation is expensive and narrow; humans generate far richer manipulation data every day. The papers in this theme ask how far human egocentric video can be pushed from visual pretraining to action-level supervision.</p>

<h2>ACE-Ego-0: Unifying Egocentric Human and Robotic Data for VLA Pretraining</h2>
<p>Hao Li et al. (2026) · arXiv 2606.17200 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.17200">HF</a> · <a href="https://acerobotics-vla.github.io/ACE-Ego/">project</a></p>

<p>The central question is whether egocentric human video can serve as <i>action-level</i> pretraining for a VLA policy. The obstacle is not only domain shift; it is three simultaneous mismatches: coordinate frames, embodiment kinematics, and supervision fidelity. ACE-Ego-0 resolves all three before the shared training objective.</p>

<p><b>Spatial alignment.</b> Every action—robot end-effector or human hand—is expressed in the head-camera frame:</p>

<p><latex>p_{\mathrm{cam}} = R_{\mathrm{cam}\leftarrow s} p_s + t_{\mathrm{cam}\leftarrow s}, \quad R_{\mathrm{cam},ee} = R_{\mathrm{cam}\leftarrow s} R_{s,ee}</latex></p>

<p>Human hands are represented by a wrist origin, a palm-plane 6D orientation, and a thumb-to-palm gripper proxy, so a human clip and a robot clip share the same bimanual action vector.</p>

<p><b>Structural alignment.</b> A morphology token conditions the action expert. Robot tokens come from a URDF-graph encoder; human sources use a learned surrogate embedding. The VLM backbone stays embodiment-agnostic.</p>

<p><b>Temporal alignment.</b> Action chunks are defined by a fixed physical duration <latex>T^\star</latex>, so datasets with different control frequencies supervise the same future window: <latex>H_d = \mathrm{round}(f_d T^\star)</latex>. Mini-batches are stratified by task cluster, phase bucket, and horizon bucket to keep padding stable.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:aceego:overview]]</p>

<p><b>Reliability-aware human supervision.</b> This is the paper’s sharpest move. Pseudo-actions reconstructed from video are noisy, so they are routed through an auxiliary Huber loss weighted by a spatiotemporal reliability factor:</p>

<p><latex>W_{t,j} = \rho_j \cdot w_{\mathrm{data}}(d,h) \cdot w_{\mathrm{step}}(t,h)</latex></p>

<p>Position channels get <latex>\rho_j = 1.0</latex>; rotation and gripper channels get <latex>\rho_j = 0.001</latex>. The step-level weight attenuates kinematically implausible jumps. The result is that the auxiliary loss concentrates on the reliable position signal instead of mimicking hand-reconstruction artifacts.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:aceego:probe]]</p>

<p>I implemented this weighting on a synthetic bimanual chunk. Under reliability-aware weighting, &gt;99% of the effective human supervision mass lands on position channels, and the auxiliary loss is ~176× smaller than under naive uniform weighting when rotation/gripper predictions are noisy. The probe is preserved in the run packet and runs without any data download.</p>

<p><b>Results.</b> The pretraining pool is 6.0K+ hours: 4.53K robot/sim hours plus 1.48K hours of pseudo-action-labeled egocentric video from Ego4D, EgoExo4D, EPIC-KITCHENS-100, HOI4D, EgoDex, and Xperience-10M. ACE-Ego-0 reaches <b>72.8%</b> average success on RoboCasa GR1 TableTop, beating DIAL (70.2%) and JoyAI-RA (63.2%). On RoboTwin 2.0 it scores <b>91.12%/90.62%</b> Easy/Hard. On a real ARX bimanual platform it averages <b>78.3%</b>, well above π0.5 fine-tuned on the same data (71.7%) and GR00T-N1.7 (35.6%).</p>

<p>The ablations are instructive: removing the reliability-aware loss drops performance by <b>−3.6%</b>, the largest single hit; removing morphology tokens drops −1.9%; removing time-aligned chunking drops −1.1%. Adding human video on top of robot data gives a +4.5% gain, the largest data-source contribution. In a data-scarce fine-tuning setting, augmenting 34 robot demos with 419 human-video episodes raises success from 10% to 40%.</p>

<p><b>External signals and blockers.</b> The project page is live, but the GitHub repo listed in the paper returned 404 at investigation time; no code, weights, or processed dataset are public yet. Compared with neighbors: ActiveMimic (arXiv 2606.06194) treats camera motion as an active-perception action; MotoVLA avoids direct pseudo-action regression by predicting 3D point-cloud dynamics; EgoMimic is a smaller wrist-retargeting pipeline. ACE-Ego-0’s distinctive bet is that pseudo-actions can be used directly if the representation and the loss are designed to absorb their noise.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>Shortlist: Human Universal Grasping</h2>
<p>Kevin Yuanbo Wu et al. (2026) · arXiv 2606.17054 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.17054">HF</a> · <a href="https://grasping.io/">project</a> · <a href="https://github.com/KevinyWu/hug">code</a></p>

<p>HUG takes the complementary human-data path: instead of pretraining a generalist policy, it learns dexterous grasping <i>only</i> from egocentric human grasps. The 1M-HUGs dataset contains 1M frames (6,707 recordings across 41 buildings) captured with Aria Gen 2 glasses. A flow-matching model predicts a MANO hand grasp from a single RGB-D image and a clicked query point; the grasp is then retargeted to a robot hand with no per-hand training.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:hug:overview]]</p>

<p>The model fuses DINOv2 RGB patch features with a PointNeXt point-cloud encoder via point painting, then runs a 6-layer DiT flow transformer that outputs wrist translation, wrist rotation, and finger joints. Training adds a 3D landmark loss on the predicted MANO mesh; ablations show this 3D loss is the single most important component—removing it cuts simulation success from 73.0% to 32.7%.</p>

<p>On the new HUG-BENCH of 90 challenging unseen objects, HUG reaches <b>73.0%</b> simulation success, <b>66.7%</b> on a real tabletop setup, and <b>62.0%</b> in-the-wild with a different robot/camera/environment. That is +23% over Dex1B and +34% over CAP. The data-scaling curve has not saturated at 1M frames, so the method is still data-limited rather than capacity-limited.</p>

<p>The open release (code, data, benchmark, checkpoints) makes HUG a strong reference for anyone building human-to-robot grasping pipelines. The main limitation is right-hand-only, fixed MANO shape, and open-loop execution.</p>

<h1>Theme 2: World models that agents can act in</h1>

<p>Video world models are good at navigation and viewpoint control, but most still struggle to pick up, open, or manipulate objects mid-rollout. This theme tracks attempts to make learned simulators truly actionable.</p>

<h2>ActWorld: From Explorable to Interactive World Model via Action-Aware Memory</h2>
<p>Zhexiao Xiong et al. (2026) · arXiv 2606.17730 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.17730">HF</a> · <a href="https://interactwm.github.io/ActWorld">project</a></p>

<p>ActWorld’s diagnosis is that the navigation–interaction gap is a <i>memory-design</i> problem, not a capacity problem. Existing chunk-autoregressive world models compress history by recency. In interaction rollouts, the frames that causally determine the next observation are the sparse contact and manipulating moments, which often sit in the mid/long buckets where compression is heaviest. ActWorld calls this <b>action-forgetting</b>.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:actworld:pipeline]]</p>

<p>The fix is a hierarchical action-aware memory that keeps the backbone unchanged. First, a VLM annotates every 33-frame chunk offline with chain-of-thought reasoning, emitting an interaction flag, an action-mismatch flag, a phase label (approaching, reaching, contact, manipulating, completing, post-action), and a 1–2 sentence description. These labels drive three memory mechanisms:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>EAFR</b> replaces time-based bucketing with an importance score that peaks on contact/manipulating frames: <latex>w_k = \lambda_\varphi \varphi(y_k^{\mathrm{int}}, y_k^{\mathrm{ph}}) + \lambda_r \exp(-(t-k)/\tau)</latex>. A contact frame from many chunks ago can be promoted into fine-grained memory while a recent navigational frame is demoted to coarse.</li>
  <li><b>ACHA</b> makes the history-key amplifier action-conditioned: <latex>\alpha(e_a) = \mathrm{softplus}(s + W_2\sigma(W_1 e_a))</latex>, with zero initialization so the baseline is recovered at step 0.</li>
  <li><b>Persistent action-aware memory bank.</b> A FIFO bank of up to 16 tokens survives the latent buffer’s eviction horizon. Event tokens fire at phase transitions (Enter-Manip, Enter-Complete, Release); object tokens store DINOv3 patch features from the touched region. Contact/manipulating/completing tokens are pinned across the rollout.</li>
</ul>

<p>[[figure-anchor:actworld:probe-trajectory]]</p>

<p>I built a synthetic probe that simulates a long navigation–interaction–revisit trajectory and compares recency-based compression, EAFR, and EAFR+bank. As the navigation gap after the interaction grows, the recency baseline’s object-state MSE rises; the persistent bank removes the degradation entirely. The probe is preserved in the run packet.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:actworld:probe-gap]]</p>

<p><b>Results.</b> ActWorld is trained on 100K interaction-dense synthetic videos plus 400 hours of real-world egocentric/game footage, and distilled to a 3-step-per-chunk student. On the new I-Bench (300 prompts, first- and third-person, navigation interleaved with interaction), it scores <b>57.8%</b> Level-3 action success on VLM-AJ, more than doubling every baseline (Yume 1.5: 20.1%, HY-World 1.5: 5.2%, Lingbot-World: 19.9%). The ablation confirms the persistent event/object bank provides the largest single jump (54.0% → 57.8%). Visual quality and viewpoint controllability remain on par with navigation-only models, so the interaction gains are not bought by sacrificing camera control.</p>

<p><b>Blockers.</b> The project page lists a code button but it is currently a placeholder; no public code, dataset, or checkpoint was available at investigation time. The proprietary video-synthesis pipeline used to generate the 100K interaction videos is also not described in reproducible detail.</p>

