<h1>Theme 3: Tokenizing and generating motion</h1>

<p>Humanoid motion generation needs both semantic pose structure and physical dynamics. The thread here asks whether a single discrete vocabulary can represent both, or whether the tokenizer itself must be structured.</p>

<h2>MotionVLA: Vision-Language-Action Model for Humanoid Motion</h2>
<p>Nonghai Zhang et al. (2026) · arXiv 2606.15142 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.15142">HF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/AIGeeksGroup/MotionVLA">code</a></p>

<p>MotionVLA starts from a spectral observation: on HumanML3D, the first five DCT coefficients capture ~93% of joint-position energy but only ~37% of joint-velocity energy. A single shared codebook therefore gets dominated by low-frequency pose statistics and under-represents high-frequency physical signals. The consequence is temporal drift, foot sliding, and contact distortion.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:motionvla:energy]]</p>

<p><b>DSFT.</b> The Dual-Stream Frequency Tokenizer splits motion into a Base stream (position/rotation) and a Phys stream (velocity). Each stream gets its own DCT truncation and BPE tokenizer. On HumanML3D, Base uses <latex>K_b = 5</latex> coefficients while Phys uses <latex>K_p = 25</latex>. The reconstructed streams are concatenated along the feature dimension:</p>

<p><latex>\mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{base}} = \mathrm{DCT}(\mathbf{M}_{\mathrm{base}})_{[:K_b]}, \quad \mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{phys}} = \mathrm{DCT}(\mathbf{M}_{\mathrm{phys}})_{[:K_p]}</latex></p>

<p><b>Unified autoregressive sequence.</b> MotionVLA extends a Qwen3.5 backbone with motion tokens and three structural markers. The target sequence is</p>

<p><latex>\mathbf{s} = [M_{\mathrm{BOS}}, b_1, \dots, b_N, M_{\mathrm{SEP}}, p_1, \dots, p_M, M_{\mathrm{EOS}}]</latex></p>

<p>Base tokens are generated first; Phys tokens attend to the full Base context through causal attention. A phase-aware logit mask enforces the Base-then-Phys order at inference.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:motionvla:probe]]</p>

<p>I reproduced the spectral argument on synthetic 1D/2D motion. With the same total DCT budget, a single-stream tokenizer uses ~0.035 tokens/frame and achieves Phys-stream MSE 0.034; DSFT uses ~0.019 tokens/frame and achieves Phys-stream MSE 0.021. The Base stream needs only 3 DCT coefficients to capture ~96% of energy, while the Phys stream needs far more. The probe is preserved in the run packet.</p>

<p><b>Results.</b> On MBench, a 2B MotionVLA reaches <b>0.55</b> Motion-Condition Consistency and <b>0.0049</b> Foot Sliding, best among compared methods. On HumanML3D, it achieves the Diversity score closest to real data and the highest MModality among generated methods. A human preference study prefers MotionVLA over ViMoGen 64% to 14% (22% ties). The method is deployed on a real Unitree G1 EDU humanoid from text prompts.</p>

<p>The ablation on Phys truncation <latex>K_p</latex> shows diminishing returns beyond 25; the backbone-scale ablation shows most gains are captured at 2B. The limitation is the fixed stream partition and fixed generation order, which may not be optimal for all motion types.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>Shortlist: Hierarchical Advantage Weighting for Online RL Fine-Tuning of VLAs</h2>
<p>Tongyan Fang et al. (2026) · arXiv 2606.17043 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.17043">HF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/ACERobotics-VLA/HABC">code</a></p>

<p>HABC addresses a practical VLA deployment problem: online RL fine-tuning from sparse binary episode outcomes. A single scalar advantage conflates two different signals—<i>viability</i> (can the task still be completed?) and <i>efficiency</i> (is the policy making progress?). HABC trains separate critic heads for each and combines their one-step advantages with a state-adaptive gate. It also restricts outcome labels to policy-execution segments, preventing credit leakage across human-intervention boundaries. On three real bimanual tasks, success rates rise from 36%/44%/12% under supervised fine-tuning to 92%/88%/38% with HABC.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p>Three patterns recur across the deep threads:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>Representation before scale.</b> ACE-Ego-0, ActWorld, and MotionVLA all win by redesigning the interface between data and model—camera-space actions, event-aware memory, and frequency-aware tokens—rather than by simply scaling parameters. The MotionVLA backbone ablation shows most of the gain at 2B; the ACE-Ego-0 ablation shows that adding human video helps more than adding parameters.</li>
  <li><b>Heterogeneous data needs heterogeneous losses.</b> ACE-Ego-0’s reliability-aware auxiliary loss, HABC’s dual-head critic, and even BadWorld’s attack on denoising velocity all reflect the same insight: not every dimension or every sample should be weighted equally.</li>
  <li><b>World models are still fragile.</b> ActWorld and Qwen-RobotWorld push interactivity and generality, but BadWorld shows that tiny adversarial perturbations can catastrophically corrupt autoregressive world-model rollouts. Robustness evaluation is lagging behind capability.</li>
</ul>

<p>The period feels like a shift from “collect more robot data” to “use the right representation for the data you already have.” Human video, latent subgoals, language actions, and frequency-aware tokens are all bids on what that representation should look like. The strongest papers in this run are the ones that make the bid concrete enough to measure.</p>
